1
00:00:01,251 --> 00:00:03,337
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

2
00:00:51,176 --> 00:00:53,053
(MOBILE RINGING)

3
00:00:53,971 --> 00:00:55,889
You're up early! What's happening?

4
00:00:55,973 --> 00:00:59,309
It's a nightmare 'cause Dad won't listen
and I'm telling you, Mum's going mental.

5
00:00:59,434 --> 00:01:02,437
Swear to God, Martha, this is epic.
You got to get in there and stop him.

6
00:01:02,521 --> 00:01:04,898
-How do I do that?
-Tell Dad he can't bring her.

7
00:01:04,982 --> 00:01:06,024
(BEEPING)

8
00:01:06,149 --> 00:01:07,776
Hold on, that's Leo. I'll call you back.

9
00:01:07,859 --> 00:01:10,153
Martha, if Mum and Dad
start to kick off,

10
00:01:10,237 --> 00:01:12,823
tell them I don't even want a party.
I didn't even ask for one.

11
00:01:12,948 --> 00:01:14,658
They can always give me
the money instead.

12
00:01:14,783 --> 00:01:16,660
Why do I have to tell them?
Why can't you?

13
00:01:16,743 --> 00:01:19,329
Hold on, that's Mum. I'll call you back.

14
00:01:20,330 --> 00:01:23,792
I don't mind your father
making a fool of himself in private,

15
00:01:23,875 --> 00:01:26,587
but this is Leo's 21st.
Everyone is going to be there,

16
00:01:26,670 --> 00:01:29,506
and the entire family
is going to look ridiculous.

17
00:01:29,590 --> 00:01:32,426
Mum, it's a party. I can't stop Dad
from bringing his girlfriend.

18
00:01:32,509 --> 00:01:34,011
(BEEPING)

19
00:01:34,136 --> 00:01:36,221
Hold on, that's Dad. I'll call you back.

20
00:01:37,723 --> 00:01:40,142
Martha, now tell your mother.

21
00:01:40,225 --> 00:01:44,479
Leo is my son,
and I'm paying for half that party.

22
00:01:44,563 --> 00:01:46,732
I'm entitled to bring who I like.

23
00:01:46,857 --> 00:01:48,900
I know, but think
what it's going to look like for Mum

24
00:01:49,026 --> 00:01:50,444
if you're standing there with Annalise.

25
00:01:50,527 --> 00:01:52,988
What's wrong with Annalise?

26
00:01:53,071 --> 00:01:54,865
Is that Martha? Say hi!

27
00:01:54,948 --> 00:01:56,617
Hi, Martha! Hi!

28
00:01:56,700 --> 00:01:57,951
Hi, Annalise.

29
00:01:58,035 --> 00:02:01,163
Big kiss! Lots of love!
See you at the party, babes!

30
00:02:01,246 --> 00:02:03,582
Now take me shopping, big boy.

31
00:02:06,710 --> 00:02:08,128
Like so!

32
00:02:09,755 --> 00:02:10,881
See?

33
00:02:27,189 --> 00:02:29,066
Oi! Watch it, mate!

34
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:56,259
I was all right till this morning,
and then...

35
00:02:56,385 --> 00:02:59,429
I don't know, I woke up
and I felt all dizzy again.

36
00:02:59,513 --> 00:03:02,307
It was worse than when I came in.

37
00:03:02,432 --> 00:03:04,142
Pulse is slightly thready.

38
00:03:04,267 --> 00:03:08,313
Well, let's see what Britain's finest
might suggest. Any ideas, Morgenstern?

39
00:03:08,522 --> 00:03:12,025
Er, dizziness could be
a sign of early onset diabetes.

40
00:03:12,109 --> 00:03:14,820
Hardly early onset,
if you'll forgive me, Miss Finnegan.

41
00:03:14,903 --> 00:03:16,863
Any more ideas? Swales?

42
00:03:16,947 --> 00:03:18,031
Um...

43
00:03:18,115 --> 00:03:21,618
-Could recommend a CT scan.
-And spend all our money?

44
00:03:21,743 --> 00:03:22,786
Jones?

45
00:03:22,869 --> 00:03:25,622
We could take bloods
and check for Méniere's disease.

46
00:03:25,747 --> 00:03:28,208
Or we could simply ask the patient.

47
00:03:28,291 --> 00:03:30,711
What did you have for dinner last night?

48
00:03:30,794 --> 00:03:31,962
I had salad.

49
00:03:32,045 --> 00:03:34,047
-And the night before?
-Salad, again.

50
00:03:34,131 --> 00:03:39,052
And salad every night for the past week,
contrary to my instructions.

51
00:03:40,387 --> 00:03:42,514
A salt deficiency, that's all.

52
00:03:42,597 --> 00:03:45,392
Simple, honest salt.

53
00:03:45,475 --> 00:03:49,020
Hippocrates himself
expounded on the virtues of salt.

54
00:03:49,104 --> 00:03:52,649
Recommended the inhalation of steam
from sea water.

55
00:03:52,774 --> 00:03:55,610
Though no doubt
if he'd been afflicted with my students,

56
00:03:55,694 --> 00:03:58,822
his oaths might have been
rather more colourful.

57
00:04:05,203 --> 00:04:08,749
Now then, Mr Smith, a very good morning
to you. How are you today?

58
00:04:08,832 --> 00:04:11,126
Oh, not so bad.
Still a bit, you know... Blah.

59
00:04:11,209 --> 00:04:15,005
John Smith, admitted yesterday
with severe abdominal pains.

60
00:04:15,088 --> 00:04:18,759
Jones, why don't you see
what you can find? Amaze me.

61
00:04:18,842 --> 00:04:21,636
It wasn't very clever
running around outside, was it?

62
00:04:21,720 --> 00:04:24,139
-Sorry?
-On Chancellor Street, this morning.

63
00:04:24,222 --> 00:04:28,226
-Came up to me and took your tie off.
-Really? What did I do that for?

64
00:04:28,310 --> 00:04:29,728
I don't know, you just did.

65
00:04:29,811 --> 00:04:32,856
Not me. I was here in bed.
Ask the nurses.

66
00:04:32,939 --> 00:04:35,317
Well, that's weird
'cause it looked like you.

67
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:38,320
-Have you got a brother?
-No, not any more. Just me.

68
00:04:38,403 --> 00:04:42,949
As time passes and I grow ever more
infirm and weary, Miss Jones...

69
00:04:43,033 --> 00:04:44,367
Sorry.

70
00:04:44,826 --> 00:04:46,495
Right.

71
00:04:47,871 --> 00:04:50,165
(HEARTS BEATING)

72
00:04:55,378 --> 00:04:57,714
I weep for future generations.

73
00:04:57,839 --> 00:05:00,884
Are you having trouble
locating the heart, Miss Jones?

74
00:05:00,967 --> 00:05:05,138
Um, I don't know. Stomach cramps?

75
00:05:05,222 --> 00:05:08,475
That is a symptom, not a diagnosis.

76
00:05:08,558 --> 00:05:10,811
And you rather failed basic techniques

77
00:05:10,894 --> 00:05:14,147
by not consulting first
with the patient's chart.

78
00:05:15,857 --> 00:05:17,484
That happened to me this morning.

79
00:05:17,567 --> 00:05:18,902
I had the same thing on the door handle.

80
00:05:19,027 --> 00:05:21,905
-And me, in the Lift.
-Well, it's only to be expected.

81
00:05:21,988 --> 00:05:23,698
There's a thunderstorm moving in

82
00:05:23,824 --> 00:05:26,576
and lightning is a form
of static electricity,

83
00:05:26,660 --> 00:05:29,663
as was first proven by... Anyone?

84
00:05:29,746 --> 00:05:31,581
Benjamin Franklin.

85
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:33,166
Correct.

86
00:05:33,250 --> 00:05:35,919
My mate, Ben. That was a day and a half.
I got rope burns off that kite.

87
00:05:36,002 --> 00:05:37,546
-And then I got soaked.
-Quite.

88
00:05:37,671 --> 00:05:39,840
And then I got electrocuted!

89
00:05:39,923 --> 00:05:41,508
Moving on.

90
00:05:41,591 --> 00:05:44,261
I think perhaps a visit
from psychiatric.

91
00:05:44,386 --> 00:05:46,513
And next, we have Mr...

92
00:05:51,142 --> 00:05:54,104
No, listen, I've worked out a plan.

93
00:05:54,229 --> 00:05:57,232
We tell Annalise that the buffet tonight
is 100% carbohydrate,

94
00:05:57,315 --> 00:05:59,484
and she won't turn up.

95
00:05:59,568 --> 00:06:01,194
I wish you'd take this seriously.

96
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:04,364
That's our inheritance
she's spending on fake tan.

97
00:06:04,447 --> 00:06:05,699
Tell you what, I'm not that far away.

98
00:06:05,782 --> 00:06:07,659
I'll meet you for a sandwich,
we can draw up a battle plan.

99
00:06:07,742 --> 00:06:10,787
What, in this weather?
I'm not going out, it's pouring down.

100
00:06:10,871 --> 00:06:12,914
It's not raining here.

101
00:06:14,457 --> 00:06:16,543
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

102
00:06:16,626 --> 00:06:19,462
God, that's weird.
It's raining right on top of you.

103
00:06:19,546 --> 00:06:22,549
-I can see it, but it's dry where I am.
-Well, you just got lucky.

104
00:06:22,632 --> 00:06:25,677
No, but it's like in cartoons,
when a man's got a cloud over his head.

105
00:06:25,802 --> 00:06:28,847
Yeah, but listen,
I'll tell you what we do...

106
00:06:31,933 --> 00:06:35,312
We tell Dad and Annalise
to get there early, about 7:30,

107
00:06:35,395 --> 00:06:37,355
and we tell Leo to get there
at the same time

108
00:06:37,480 --> 00:06:38,857
so we can do all that birthday stuff.

109
00:06:38,982 --> 00:06:41,151
We tell Mum to get there
for about 8:30-9:00,

110
00:06:41,276 --> 00:06:44,571
then that gives me time
to have a word with Annalise and...

111
00:06:44,654 --> 00:06:46,156
What?

112
00:06:46,281 --> 00:06:48,658
-The rain.
-It's only rain.

113
00:06:48,783 --> 00:06:50,952
Martha, have you seen the rain?

114
00:06:51,077 --> 00:06:52,871
Why is everyone fussing about rain?

115
00:06:52,996 --> 00:06:54,247
It's going up.

116
00:06:54,331 --> 00:06:56,333
The rain is going up.

117
00:07:28,949 --> 00:07:31,034
What the hell was that?

118
00:07:31,159 --> 00:07:33,161
Are you all right?

119
00:07:33,244 --> 00:07:36,081
I think so, yeah.

120
00:07:36,206 --> 00:07:38,667
It felt like an earthquake or...

121
00:07:38,750 --> 00:07:41,252
Martha, it's night.

122
00:07:42,337 --> 00:07:46,466
-But it was lunch time...
-It's not night.

123
00:07:46,800 --> 00:07:50,387
But it's got to be. It's dark.

124
00:07:51,346 --> 00:07:54,349
-We're on the moon!
-Can't be.

125
00:07:55,100 --> 00:07:57,894
We're on the moon.

126
00:07:58,019 --> 00:08:00,188
We're on the bloody moon.

127
00:08:42,355 --> 00:08:44,566
I'm sorry, miss, no.

128
00:08:44,649 --> 00:08:46,109
Oh, my God.

129
00:08:46,192 --> 00:08:48,319
(SIREN WAILING)

130
00:08:56,870 --> 00:08:59,164
Martha? Martha, can you hear me?

131
00:09:00,331 --> 00:09:01,583
Martha?

132
00:09:02,917 --> 00:09:05,128
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

133
00:09:07,297 --> 00:09:09,549
Somebody help! Somebody help me!

134
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:29,152
-Have you seen...
-I'm sorry, I can't.

135
00:09:31,488 --> 00:09:33,406
All right now, everyone, back to bed.

136
00:09:33,490 --> 00:09:36,993
We've got an emergency,
but we'll sort it out. Don't worry.

137
00:09:38,036 --> 00:09:41,498
It's real. It's really real.

138
00:09:42,499 --> 00:09:46,044
-Hold on.
-Don't! We'll lose all the air!

139
00:09:46,211 --> 00:09:49,422
But they're not exactly airtight.
If the air was gonna get sucked out,

140
00:09:49,506 --> 00:09:51,633
it would've happened straightaway,
but it didn't.

141
00:09:51,716 --> 00:09:54,135
-So, how come?
-Very good point!

142
00:09:54,219 --> 00:09:56,846
-Brilliant, in fact. What was your name?
-Martha.

143
00:09:56,930 --> 00:09:58,973
And it was Jones, wasn't it?

144
00:09:59,057 --> 00:10:02,018
Well, Martha Jones, question is,
how are we still breathing?

145
00:10:02,143 --> 00:10:03,353
We can't be!

146
00:10:03,436 --> 00:10:04,896
Obviously we are so don't waste my time.

147
00:10:04,979 --> 00:10:07,607
Martha, what have we got? Is there
a balcony on this floor, or a veranda?

148
00:10:07,690 --> 00:10:10,026
By the patients' lounge, yeah.

149
00:10:10,110 --> 00:10:12,529
-You fancy going out?
-Okay.

150
00:10:12,654 --> 00:10:15,031
-We might die.
-We might not.

151
00:10:16,324 --> 00:10:17,992
Good. Come on.

152
00:10:18,076 --> 00:10:20,245
Not her, she'd hold us up.

153
00:10:40,265 --> 00:10:42,058
(DOCTOR INHALING)

154
00:10:46,771 --> 00:10:48,773
We've got air.

155
00:10:51,067 --> 00:10:53,903
-How does that work?
-Just be glad it does.

156
00:11:01,411 --> 00:11:03,538
I've got a party tonight.

157
00:11:04,372 --> 00:11:06,666
It's my brother's 21st.

158
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:10,753
My mother's gonna be really... Really...

159
00:11:11,880 --> 00:11:13,423
-You okay?
-Yeah.

160
00:11:13,506 --> 00:11:14,632
-Sure?
-Yeah.

161
00:11:14,716 --> 00:11:16,593
-Do you want to go back in?
-No way.

162
00:11:16,718 --> 00:11:21,097
I mean, we could die any minute,
but all the same, it's beautiful.

163
00:11:21,181 --> 00:11:22,348
Do you think?

164
00:11:22,432 --> 00:11:26,436
How many people want to go to the moon?
And here we are.

165
00:11:27,187 --> 00:11:29,314
Standing in the Earth light.

166
00:11:30,565 --> 00:11:32,609
What do you think happened?

167
00:11:33,276 --> 00:11:34,986
What do you think?

168
00:11:36,279 --> 00:11:39,073
Extraterrestrial. It's got to be.

169
00:11:39,157 --> 00:11:43,119
I don't know, a few years ago that
would've sounded mad, but these days...

170
00:11:43,203 --> 00:11:48,124
That spaceship flying into Big Ben.
Christmas. Those Cybermen things.

171
00:11:51,628 --> 00:11:54,339
I had a cousin, Adeola.

172
00:11:55,381 --> 00:11:57,592
She worked at Canary Wharf.

173
00:11:58,468 --> 00:12:00,428
She never came home.

174
00:12:02,013 --> 00:12:04,098
I'm sorry.

175
00:12:04,182 --> 00:12:05,642
Yeah.

176
00:12:06,768 --> 00:12:11,022
I was there, in the battle. It was...

177
00:12:15,693 --> 00:12:18,571
I promise you, Mr Smith,
we will find a way out.

178
00:12:18,655 --> 00:12:21,199
If we can travel to the moon,
then we can travel back.

179
00:12:21,282 --> 00:12:22,450
There's got to be a way.

180
00:12:22,533 --> 00:12:24,827
It's not Smith. That's not my real name.

181
00:12:24,911 --> 00:12:27,497
-Who are you, then?
-I'm the Doctor.

182
00:12:27,580 --> 00:12:30,083
Me, too, if I ever pass my exams.

183
00:12:30,166 --> 00:12:32,043
What is it then, Dr Smith?

184
00:12:32,126 --> 00:12:35,421
-Just the Doctor.
-How do you mean, just the Doctor?

185
00:12:35,964 --> 00:12:38,007
Just the Doctor.

186
00:12:38,091 --> 00:12:40,551
-What, people call you "the Doctor"?
-Yeah.

187
00:12:40,677 --> 00:12:45,390
Well, I'm not. Far as I'm concerned,
you've got to earn that title.

188
00:12:45,515 --> 00:12:48,601
Well, I'd better make a start, then.
Let's have a look.

189
00:12:48,685 --> 00:12:50,979
There must be some sort of...

190
00:12:53,106 --> 00:12:54,774
Force-field.

191
00:12:55,733 --> 00:12:57,568
Keeping the air in.

192
00:12:57,694 --> 00:13:00,697
But if that's like a bubble
sealing us in,

193
00:13:00,780 --> 00:13:03,366
that means this is the only air
we've got.

194
00:13:03,449 --> 00:13:06,786
-What happens when it runs out?
-How many people in this hospital?

195
00:13:06,869 --> 00:13:08,538
Don't know, a thousand?

196
00:13:08,621 --> 00:13:13,251
-One thousand people, suffocating.
-Why would anyone do that?

197
00:13:13,334 --> 00:13:15,169
(RUMBLING)

198
00:13:15,253 --> 00:13:16,879
Heads up! Ask him yourself.

199
00:14:19,692 --> 00:14:21,569
MARTHA: Aliens.

200
00:14:21,652 --> 00:14:23,613
That's aliens!

201
00:14:23,988 --> 00:14:25,823
Real, proper aliens.

202
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:28,451
Judoon.

203
00:14:45,468 --> 00:14:47,011
Mr Stoker?

204
00:14:47,095 --> 00:14:50,932
I'm sorry, I didn't know
who else to ask, but can you help me?

205
00:14:51,015 --> 00:14:53,684
I think we've gone
beyond aspirin, Miss...

206
00:14:53,768 --> 00:14:54,894
Finnegan.

207
00:14:54,977 --> 00:14:56,854
Names! What are names now

208
00:14:56,938 --> 00:15:00,566
when something unnameable
is marching towards us across the moon?

209
00:15:00,650 --> 00:15:04,028
Two more years, I thought. Two more
years and then retire to Florida.

210
00:15:04,153 --> 00:15:08,157
But there is Florida, in the sky.
I can see it.

211
00:15:08,241 --> 00:15:13,329
My daughter. She's still in university.
I am never going to see her again.

212
00:15:13,413 --> 00:15:16,958
-But I need help, Mr Stoker.
-I can't do anything!

213
00:15:17,041 --> 00:15:18,751
Oh, I think you can.

214
00:15:21,587 --> 00:15:24,090
What do you two want?
It's a bit late to sign for anything.

215
00:15:24,173 --> 00:15:28,302
These are my lovely boys.
I prefer not to get my hands dirty.

216
00:15:28,386 --> 00:15:31,264
-I'm sorry?
-You see, there are great tests to come,

217
00:15:31,347 --> 00:15:33,224
and terrible deeds.

218
00:15:33,349 --> 00:15:35,017
Some of them my own.

219
00:15:35,101 --> 00:15:38,604
But if I'm to survive this, I need you.

220
00:15:38,688 --> 00:15:42,525
-What are you talking about?
-Blood. Specifically, yours.

221
00:15:44,485 --> 00:15:46,404
What are you doing?

222
00:15:46,737 --> 00:15:48,197
What are you doing?

223
00:15:48,281 --> 00:15:50,032
Will you let go of me!
What the hell? Let go!

224
00:15:50,116 --> 00:15:52,577
You see, I was only salt deficient

225
00:15:52,660 --> 00:15:55,621
because I'm so very good
at absorbing it.

226
00:15:55,705 --> 00:15:58,499
But now I need fire in my veins.

227
00:15:58,583 --> 00:16:03,546
And who better than a consultant,
with blood full of salty fats

228
00:16:03,629 --> 00:16:08,551
and vintage wines
and all those Michelin star sauces?

229
00:16:09,427 --> 00:16:11,012
Who are you?

230
00:16:11,095 --> 00:16:14,474
Oh, I'm a survivor, Mr Stoker.

231
00:16:14,557 --> 00:16:15,933
At any cost.

232
00:16:17,393 --> 00:16:18,561
Look!

233
00:16:20,771 --> 00:16:23,065
I've even brought a straw.

234
00:16:26,736 --> 00:16:28,571
(SCREAMING)

235
00:17:19,705 --> 00:17:23,960
Bo! Sco! Fo! Do! No!
Kro! Blo! Co! Sho! Ro!

236
00:17:30,633 --> 00:17:34,679
We are citizens of planet Earth.
We welcome you in peace.

237
00:17:34,804 --> 00:17:36,472
(GROWLING)

238
00:17:39,267 --> 00:17:42,186
Please don't hurt me. I was just trying
to help, I'm sorry. Don't hurt me.

239
00:17:42,311 --> 00:17:44,480
Please don't hurt me.

240
00:17:44,605 --> 00:17:47,733
Please don't hurt me. I was just trying
to help, I'm sorry. Don't hurt me.

241
00:17:47,817 --> 00:17:48,943
Please don't hurt me.

242
00:17:49,026 --> 00:17:53,155
Language assimilated.
Designation, Earth English.

243
00:17:53,281 --> 00:17:55,241
You will be catalogued.

244
00:17:56,993 --> 00:17:58,661
Category, human.

245
00:18:05,001 --> 00:18:06,711
Catalogue all suspects.

246
00:18:17,972 --> 00:18:20,016
Aw, look down there,
you've got a little shop.

247
00:18:20,099 --> 00:18:23,853
-I like a little shop.
-Never mind that. What are Judoon?

248
00:18:23,936 --> 00:18:26,772
They're like police.
Well, police-for-hire.

249
00:18:26,856 --> 00:18:30,401
-They're more like interplanetary thugs.
-And they brought us to the moon?

250
00:18:30,484 --> 00:18:32,320
Neutral territory.
According to Galactic Law,

251
00:18:32,445 --> 00:18:35,698
they've got no jurisdiction
over the Earth so they isolated it.

252
00:18:35,781 --> 00:18:40,411
That rain and lightning, that was them
using an 120 Scoop.

253
00:18:40,536 --> 00:18:44,665
Why are you on about, Galactic Law?
I mean, where did you get that from?

254
00:18:48,044 --> 00:18:49,295
JUDOON: Human.

255
00:18:49,378 --> 00:18:52,006
If they're police, are we under arrest?

256
00:18:52,089 --> 00:18:54,383
Are we trespassing on the moon
or something?

257
00:18:54,467 --> 00:18:58,763
No, but I like that! Good thinking.
No, wish it were that simple.

258
00:18:58,888 --> 00:19:01,724
They're making a catalogue, that means
they're after something non-human,

259
00:19:01,849 --> 00:19:03,643
which is very bad news for me.

260
00:19:03,726 --> 00:19:05,561
Why?

261
00:19:07,938 --> 00:19:10,316
Oh, you're kidding me?

262
00:19:10,399 --> 00:19:12,360
Don't be ridiculous.

263
00:19:13,486 --> 00:19:15,446
Stop looking at me like that.

264
00:19:15,571 --> 00:19:17,239
Come on, then.

265
00:19:19,909 --> 00:19:21,535
Troop 5, floor one.

266
00:19:21,619 --> 00:19:23,537
Troop 6, floor two.

267
00:19:23,621 --> 00:19:27,166
Identify humans
and find the transgressor.

268
00:19:27,249 --> 00:19:28,751
Find it!

269
00:19:40,262 --> 00:19:41,764
Prepare to be catalogued!

270
00:19:41,847 --> 00:19:44,600
Do what they say. All they want to do
is shine this light thing.

271
00:19:44,684 --> 00:19:48,187
It's all right, they're not
going to hurt us. Just listen to them.

272
00:19:53,943 --> 00:19:56,320
Witness the crime.

273
00:19:56,404 --> 00:20:00,157
Charge, physical assault. Plea, guilty.

274
00:20:00,741 --> 00:20:02,618
Sentence, execution.

275
00:20:07,790 --> 00:20:09,542
You didn't have to do that.

276
00:20:09,625 --> 00:20:11,460
Justice is swift.

277
00:20:15,297 --> 00:20:17,383
(BUZZING)

278
00:20:17,925 --> 00:20:19,885
They've reached the third floor.

279
00:20:19,969 --> 00:20:22,096
-What's that thing?
-Sonic screwdriver.

280
00:20:22,179 --> 00:20:24,432
Well, if you're not
going to answer me properly.

281
00:20:24,515 --> 00:20:27,393
No, really, it is!
It's a screwdriver and it's...sonic.

282
00:20:27,476 --> 00:20:28,769
Look.

283
00:20:28,894 --> 00:20:31,564
What else have you got? A laser spanner?

284
00:20:31,647 --> 00:20:34,316
I did, but it was stolen
by Emily Pankhurst. Cheeky woman.

285
00:20:34,400 --> 00:20:36,610
What's wrong with this computer?

286
00:20:36,694 --> 00:20:39,196
Judoon must have locked it down.

287
00:20:40,197 --> 00:20:43,033
Judoon platoon upon the moon.

288
00:20:43,159 --> 00:20:45,327
I was just travelling past,
I swear, I was just wandering.

289
00:20:45,453 --> 00:20:47,204
I wasn't looking for trouble.
Honestly, I wasn't.

290
00:20:47,329 --> 00:20:49,331
But I noticed these plasma coils
around the hospital.

291
00:20:49,457 --> 00:20:52,209
That lightning, that's a plasma coil,
it's been building up for two days now.

292
00:20:52,334 --> 00:20:54,253
So I checked in, I thought
something was going on inside.

293
00:20:54,336 --> 00:20:56,964
Turns out the plasma coils
were the Judoon up above.

294
00:20:57,047 --> 00:21:00,593
-What are they looking for?
-Something that looks human, but isn't.

295
00:21:00,718 --> 00:21:04,013
-Like you, apparently.
-Like me, but not me.

296
00:21:04,096 --> 00:21:07,266
-Haven't they got a photo?
-Might be a shape-changer.

297
00:21:07,349 --> 00:21:10,019
Whatever it is, can't you just
leave the Judoon to find it?

298
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:12,772
If they declare the hospital guilty
of harbouring a fugitive,

299
00:21:12,897 --> 00:21:14,523
they'll sentence it to execution.

300
00:21:14,607 --> 00:21:16,192
-All of us?
-Oh, yes.

301
00:21:16,317 --> 00:21:18,819
But if I can find
this thing first... Oh!

302
00:21:18,903 --> 00:21:21,280
Do you see?
They're thick. Judoon are thick.

303
00:21:21,363 --> 00:21:23,240
They are so completely thick,
they've wiped the records!

304
00:21:23,324 --> 00:21:24,450
Oh, that's clever.

305
00:21:24,533 --> 00:21:26,494
-What are we looking for?
-I don't know.

306
00:21:26,577 --> 00:21:29,288
Say, any patient admitted
in the past week with unusual symptoms.

307
00:21:29,371 --> 00:21:30,956
Maybe there's a backup.

308
00:21:31,040 --> 00:21:34,960
Just keep working, I'll go
and ask Mr Stoker. He might know.

309
00:21:40,716 --> 00:21:42,218
Mr Stoker...

310
00:21:42,301 --> 00:21:44,386
(SLURPING)

311
00:21:50,351 --> 00:21:52,061
Kill her!

312
00:21:53,729 --> 00:21:55,481
-I've restored the backup.
-I found her!

313
00:21:55,564 --> 00:21:57,525
You did what?

314
00:21:57,608 --> 00:21:58,818
Run!

315
00:22:37,648 --> 00:22:39,233
Quick!

316
00:22:47,950 --> 00:22:49,827
When I say "now", press the button.

317
00:22:49,910 --> 00:22:52,246
-But I don't know which one.
-Then find out!

318
00:23:08,971 --> 00:23:10,222
Now!

319
00:23:21,984 --> 00:23:24,236
What did you do?

320
00:23:24,320 --> 00:23:28,198
Increased the radiation by 5,000%.
Killed him dead.

321
00:23:28,282 --> 00:23:31,827
-But isn't that gonna kill you?
-Nah, it's only roentgen radiation.

322
00:23:31,952 --> 00:23:33,871
We used to play with roentgen bricks
in the nursery.

323
00:23:33,954 --> 00:23:37,041
It's safe for you to come out.
I've absorbed it all.

324
00:23:37,124 --> 00:23:39,501
Alll need to do is expel it.

325
00:23:41,253 --> 00:23:43,839
See, if I concentrate,

326
00:23:43,923 --> 00:23:47,760
shift the radiation out of my body
and into one spot.

327
00:23:47,843 --> 00:23:49,053
(GRUNTS)

328
00:23:49,178 --> 00:23:51,388
Say, my left shoe.

329
00:23:51,513 --> 00:23:53,766
Here we go. Here we go. Easy does it.

330
00:23:54,725 --> 00:23:57,686
Out, out, out, out, out, out, out...

331
00:23:57,770 --> 00:23:59,146
Ow, ow, ow!

332
00:23:59,229 --> 00:24:02,441
(EXCLAIMS) Itches, itches,
itches, itches!

333
00:24:03,359 --> 00:24:05,194
Hold on.

334
00:24:05,653 --> 00:24:08,614
-Done!
-You're completely mad.

335
00:24:08,697 --> 00:24:11,283
You're right, I look daft with one shoe.

336
00:24:14,662 --> 00:24:16,705
Barefoot on the moon!

337
00:24:17,915 --> 00:24:21,043
So what is that thing?
And where's it from, Planet Zovirax?

338
00:24:21,126 --> 00:24:24,546
It's just a Slab. They're called Slabs.

339
00:24:24,672 --> 00:24:26,799
Basic slave drones, you see.

340
00:24:26,882 --> 00:24:30,970
Solid leather all the way through.
Someone has got one hell of a fetish.

341
00:24:31,053 --> 00:24:33,263
But it was that woman, Miss Finnegan.

342
00:24:33,347 --> 00:24:36,225
It was working for her,
just like a servant.

343
00:24:36,350 --> 00:24:38,978
-My sonic screwdriver!
-She was one of the patients, but...

344
00:24:39,061 --> 00:24:40,562
Burnt out my sonic screwdriver!

345
00:24:40,646 --> 00:24:42,856
She had this straw,
like some sort of vampire.

346
00:24:42,940 --> 00:24:45,693
-I love my sonic screwdriver!
-Doctor!

347
00:24:46,485 --> 00:24:48,153
Sorry.

348
00:24:48,237 --> 00:24:50,864
-You called me Doctor.
-Anyway...

349
00:24:50,948 --> 00:24:54,660
Miss Finnegan is the alien.
She was drinking Mr Stoker's blood.

350
00:24:54,743 --> 00:24:58,497
Funny time to take a snack.
You'd think she'd be hiding.

351
00:24:58,580 --> 00:25:00,374
Unless... No!

352
00:25:01,166 --> 00:25:03,460
Yes! That's it! Wait a minute.

353
00:25:03,544 --> 00:25:06,505
Yes! Shape-changer,
internal shape-changer!

354
00:25:06,588 --> 00:25:08,674
She wasn't drinking blood,
she was assimilating it.

355
00:25:12,136 --> 00:25:14,138
JUDOON: Prepare to be catalogued!

356
00:25:14,221 --> 00:25:16,056
(ALL SCREAMING)

357
00:25:20,310 --> 00:25:21,562
Human.

358
00:25:25,983 --> 00:25:28,402
If she can assimilate Mr Stoker's blood,
mimic the biology,

359
00:25:28,485 --> 00:25:30,821
she'll register as human.

360
00:25:30,946 --> 00:25:33,574
We've got to find her
and show the Judoon. Come on!

361
00:25:34,283 --> 00:25:35,534
Human.

362
00:25:58,307 --> 00:26:01,727
That's the thing about Slabs.
They always travel in pairs.

363
00:26:02,269 --> 00:26:05,314
-What about you?
-What about me what?

364
00:26:05,439 --> 00:26:08,817
Haven't you got backup?
You must have a partner or something.

365
00:26:12,154 --> 00:26:14,323
Humans! We're stuck on the moon,
running out of air,

366
00:26:14,448 --> 00:26:16,366
with Judoon and a bloodsucking criminal,

367
00:26:16,450 --> 00:26:18,911
and you're asking personal questions.
Come on.

368
00:26:18,994 --> 00:26:20,662
I like that. "Humans!"

369
00:26:20,788 --> 00:26:23,707
I'm still not convinced you're an alien.

370
00:26:24,166 --> 00:26:25,751
Non-human!

371
00:26:25,834 --> 00:26:28,170
-Oh, my God, you really are!
-And again.

372
00:26:48,065 --> 00:26:50,526
They've done this floor. Come on.

373
00:26:52,027 --> 00:26:54,780
The Judoon are logical
and just a little bit thick.

374
00:26:54,863 --> 00:26:58,742
They won't go back to check a floor
they've checked already. If we're lucky.

375
00:26:58,826 --> 00:27:00,452
How much oxygen is there?

376
00:27:00,536 --> 00:27:04,289
Not enough for all these people.
We're gonna run out.

377
00:27:04,373 --> 00:27:06,458
How you feeling? You all right?

378
00:27:06,542 --> 00:27:08,919
-Running on adrenalin.
-Welcome to my world.

379
00:27:09,044 --> 00:27:10,420
What about the Judoon?

380
00:27:10,546 --> 00:27:13,048
Great big lung reserves.
It won't slow them down.

381
00:27:13,173 --> 00:27:16,218
-Where's Mr Stoker's office?
-It's this way.

382
00:27:25,811 --> 00:27:28,063
She's gone. She was here.

383
00:27:30,232 --> 00:27:33,193
Drained him dry. Every last drop.

384
00:27:33,318 --> 00:27:36,613
-I was right, she's a Plasmavore.
-What's she doing on Earth?

385
00:27:36,738 --> 00:27:40,993
Hiding, on the run.
Like Ronald Biggs in Rio de Janeiro.

386
00:27:41,076 --> 00:27:44,121
What's she doing now?
She's still not safe.

387
00:27:44,246 --> 00:27:46,039
The Judoon could execute us all.
Come on.

388
00:27:46,123 --> 00:27:47,875
Wait a minute.

389
00:27:58,093 --> 00:27:59,595
Think, think, think.

390
00:27:59,678 --> 00:28:02,973
If I was a wanted Plasmavore
surrounded by police, what would I do?

391
00:28:03,098 --> 00:28:06,310
Oh! She's as clever as me.

392
00:28:06,393 --> 00:28:07,603
Almost.

393
00:28:07,728 --> 00:28:08,854
(CRASHING)

394
00:28:08,937 --> 00:28:11,440
Find the non-human! Execute!

395
00:28:11,523 --> 00:28:13,567
Martha, stay here.
I need time, you've got to hold them up.

396
00:28:13,650 --> 00:28:15,527
-How do I do that?
-Just forgive me for this.

397
00:28:15,611 --> 00:28:19,531
It could save a thousand lives and
it means nothing. Honestly, nothing.

398
00:28:28,207 --> 00:28:29,666
That was nothing?

399
00:28:57,152 --> 00:28:59,154
Have you seen? There are these things!

400
00:28:59,238 --> 00:29:01,865
These great, big space rhino things.

401
00:29:01,949 --> 00:29:05,410
I mean, rhinos from space,
and we're on the moon!

402
00:29:05,494 --> 00:29:07,746
Great, big space rhinos with guns!
On the moon!

403
00:29:07,829 --> 00:29:09,957
I only came in for my bunions! Look!

404
00:29:10,040 --> 00:29:12,292
All fixed now, perfectly good treatment,
the nurses were lovely.

405
00:29:12,376 --> 00:29:14,461
I said to my wife,
"I'd recommend this place to anyone."

406
00:29:14,544 --> 00:29:18,257
But then we end up on the moon!
And did I mention the rhinos?

407
00:29:18,340 --> 00:29:19,883
Hold him.

408
00:29:24,638 --> 00:29:27,474
Find the non-human! Execute!

409
00:29:33,188 --> 00:29:35,816
Now, listen,
I know who you're looking for.

410
00:29:35,899 --> 00:29:38,610
She's this woman.
She calls herself Florence.

411
00:29:39,861 --> 00:29:40,904
Human.

412
00:29:40,988 --> 00:29:43,657
Wait. Non-human trace suspected.

413
00:29:43,740 --> 00:29:45,993
Non-human element confirmed.

414
00:29:46,118 --> 00:29:48,287
Authorise full scan.

415
00:29:49,121 --> 00:29:50,497
(MUMBLES)

416
00:29:50,580 --> 00:29:52,291
What are you?

417
00:29:52,541 --> 00:29:54,418
What are you?

418
00:29:55,127 --> 00:29:59,131
That big machine thing,
is it supposed to be making that noise?

419
00:29:59,214 --> 00:30:00,674
You wouldn't understand.

420
00:30:00,799 --> 00:30:04,594
But isn't that
a magnetic resonance imaging thing?

421
00:30:04,678 --> 00:30:08,140
Like a ginormous sort of a magnet?
I did Magnetics GCSE.

422
00:30:08,223 --> 00:30:10,058
Well, I failed, but all the same.

423
00:30:10,142 --> 00:30:13,895
A magnet with its setting
now increased to 50,000 Tesla.

424
00:30:14,021 --> 00:30:15,981
Ooh, that's a bit strong, isn't it?

425
00:30:16,064 --> 00:30:17,899
It'll send out a magnetic pulse

426
00:30:18,025 --> 00:30:21,153
that'll fry the brainstems
of every living thing

427
00:30:21,236 --> 00:30:24,406
within 250,000 miles.

428
00:30:24,573 --> 00:30:27,367
Except for me. Safe in this room.

429
00:30:27,451 --> 00:30:30,912
But hold on, hold on.
I did Geography GCSE, I passed that one.

430
00:30:31,038 --> 00:30:32,914
Doesn't that distance include the Earth?

431
00:30:32,998 --> 00:30:36,168
Only the side facing the moon.
The other half will survive.

432
00:30:36,251 --> 00:30:37,711
Call it my little gift.

433
00:30:37,794 --> 00:30:40,130
Sorry, you'll have to excuse me,
I'm a little bit out of my depth.

434
00:30:40,255 --> 00:30:42,883
I've spent the past 15 years
working as a postman. Hence the bunion.

435
00:30:42,966 --> 00:30:44,134
Why would you do that?

436
00:30:44,259 --> 00:30:48,930
With everyone dead, the Judoon ships
will be mine to make my escape.

437
00:30:49,056 --> 00:30:52,267
No, that's weird. You're talking
like you're some sort of an alien.

438
00:30:52,351 --> 00:30:53,477
Quite so.

439
00:30:53,560 --> 00:30:54,770
-No!
-Oh, yes.

440
00:30:54,853 --> 00:30:56,897
-You're joshing me!
-I am not.

441
00:30:57,022 --> 00:31:00,192
I'm talking to an alien, in a hospital?

442
00:31:00,275 --> 00:31:02,110
What, has this place got
an ET department?

443
00:31:02,194 --> 00:31:06,073
It's the perfect hiding place. Blood
banks downstairs for a midnight feast.

444
00:31:06,156 --> 00:31:08,992
And all this equipment
ready to arm myself with

445
00:31:09,076 --> 00:31:11,161
should the police come looking.

446
00:31:11,286 --> 00:31:13,163
So, those rhinos,
they're looking for you!

447
00:31:13,288 --> 00:31:17,250
Yes. But I'm hidden.

448
00:31:17,834 --> 00:31:22,714
Oh, right. Maybe that's why
they're increasing their scans.

449
00:31:22,798 --> 00:31:24,591
They're doing what?

450
00:31:24,716 --> 00:31:27,177
Big Chief Rhino boy, he said,
"No sign of a non-human.

451
00:31:27,302 --> 00:31:30,639
"We must increase our scans
up to setting two."

452
00:31:30,722 --> 00:31:33,392
-Then I must assimilate again.
-What does that mean?

453
00:31:33,475 --> 00:31:35,769
I must appear to be human.

454
00:31:35,852 --> 00:31:38,605
Well, you're welcome to come home
and meet the wife. She'd be honoured.

455
00:31:38,688 --> 00:31:39,981
We can have cake.

456
00:31:40,065 --> 00:31:43,235
Why should I have cake?
I've got my little straw.

457
00:31:43,902 --> 00:31:46,905
That's nice. Milkshake? I like banana.

458
00:31:46,988 --> 00:31:48,907
You're quite the funny man.

459
00:31:48,990 --> 00:31:53,328
And yet, I think, laughing on purpose
at the darkness.

460
00:31:53,995 --> 00:31:57,290
I think it's time you found some peace.
Steady him.

461
00:32:00,836 --> 00:32:04,923
-What are you doing?
-I'm afraid this is going to hurt.

462
00:32:05,006 --> 00:32:09,344
But if it's any consolation,
the dead don't tend to remember.

463
00:32:12,180 --> 00:32:13,974
Confirm. Human.

464
00:32:14,057 --> 00:32:17,227
Traces of facial contact with non-human.

465
00:32:17,310 --> 00:32:18,979
Continue the search!

466
00:32:19,062 --> 00:32:21,189
-You will need this.
-What's that for?

467
00:32:21,273 --> 00:32:22,899
Compensation.

468
00:32:41,710 --> 00:32:44,838
Now, see what you've done?
This poor man just died of fright.

469
00:32:44,921 --> 00:32:46,256
Scan him!

470
00:32:50,177 --> 00:32:51,720
Confirmation, deceased.

471
00:32:51,845 --> 00:32:54,431
No, he can't be!
Let me through. Let me see him.

472
00:32:54,556 --> 00:32:56,475
Stop. Case closed.

473
00:32:56,558 --> 00:32:58,310
But it was her!

474
00:32:58,393 --> 00:33:01,104
She killed him. She did it.
She murdered him!

475
00:33:01,229 --> 00:33:05,066
Judoon have no authority
over human crime.

476
00:33:05,150 --> 00:33:08,445
-But she's not human!
-Oh, but I am. I've been catalogued.

477
00:33:08,570 --> 00:33:10,739
But she's not. She assim...

478
00:33:11,198 --> 00:33:13,074
Wait a minute.

479
00:33:13,200 --> 00:33:16,411
You drank his blood? The Doctor's blood!

480
00:33:18,413 --> 00:33:20,957
Oh, I don't mind. Scan all you like.

481
00:33:21,625 --> 00:33:24,252
-Non-human!
-But... What?

482
00:33:24,336 --> 00:33:26,421
Confirm analysis.

483
00:33:27,047 --> 00:33:29,674
Oh, but there's a mistake, surely.
I'm human.

484
00:33:29,758 --> 00:33:31,301
I'm as human as they come.

485
00:33:31,426 --> 00:33:33,803
He gave his life so they'd find you.

486
00:33:33,887 --> 00:33:37,265
Confirm, Plasmavore.
Charged with the crime

487
00:33:37,349 --> 00:33:41,061
of murdering the Child Princess
of Padrivole Regency Nine.

488
00:33:41,144 --> 00:33:43,355
Well, she deserved it!

489
00:33:43,438 --> 00:33:47,108
Those pink cheeks and those blonde curls
and that simpering voice.

490
00:33:47,234 --> 00:33:50,904
She was begging for the bite
of a Plasmavore!

491
00:33:50,987 --> 00:33:54,699
-Then you confess?
-Confess? I'm proud of it!

492
00:33:54,783 --> 00:33:56,660
Slab, stop them!

493
00:34:01,665 --> 00:34:04,459
Verdict, guilty. Sentence, execution.

494
00:34:09,005 --> 00:34:11,424
Enjoy your victory, Judoon.

495
00:34:11,508 --> 00:34:15,136
Because you're going to burn with me!
Burn in hell!

496
00:34:22,936 --> 00:34:24,729
Case closed.

497
00:34:24,813 --> 00:34:27,065
But what did she mean, burn with me?

498
00:34:27,148 --> 00:34:30,485
The scanner shouldn't be doing that.
She's done something.

499
00:34:33,363 --> 00:34:34,781
(BEEPING RAPIDLY)

500
00:34:34,864 --> 00:34:39,160
Scans detect lethal acceleration
of mono-magnetic pulse.

501
00:34:39,244 --> 00:34:41,997
Well, do something! Stop it!

502
00:34:42,122 --> 00:34:46,084
Our jurisdiction has ended.
Judoon will evacuate.

503
00:34:46,167 --> 00:34:49,462
What? You can't just leave it!
What's it gonna do?

504
00:34:49,546 --> 00:34:51,506
All units withdraw!

505
00:35:05,103 --> 00:35:08,023
What about the air?
We're running out of air.

506
00:35:19,200 --> 00:35:20,744
You can't go!

507
00:35:20,827 --> 00:35:23,913
That thing's gonna explode,
and it's your fault!

508
00:35:31,838 --> 00:35:34,883
One, two, three, four, five.

509
00:35:36,051 --> 00:35:38,887
One, two, three, four, five.

510
00:35:40,972 --> 00:35:42,182
Two hearts!

511
00:35:44,059 --> 00:35:47,062
One, two, three, four, five.

512
00:35:48,396 --> 00:35:51,232
One, two, three, four, five.

513
00:36:05,747 --> 00:36:07,374
The scanner...

514
00:36:07,749 --> 00:36:09,626
She did something.

515
00:36:44,452 --> 00:36:46,538
Oh! The sonic!

516
00:37:42,469 --> 00:37:46,014
Come on, come on,
come on, come on, please.

517
00:37:46,139 --> 00:37:48,516
Come on, Judoon, reverse it.

518
00:37:50,185 --> 00:37:52,520
It's raining, Martha!

519
00:37:52,645 --> 00:37:54,564
It's raining on the moon.

520
00:38:13,041 --> 00:38:14,793
MAN: Pass me the first aid kit.

521
00:38:18,046 --> 00:38:21,132
I said I represent the human race.

522
00:38:21,216 --> 00:38:24,219
I told them, you can't do that.
I said...

523
00:38:24,344 --> 00:38:27,555
Martha! Oh, my God,
I thought you were dead.

524
00:38:27,680 --> 00:38:30,809
What happened? It was so weird!

525
00:38:30,892 --> 00:38:33,520
The police wouldn't say, they didn't
have a clue. I tried phoning.

526
00:38:33,603 --> 00:38:36,397
Mum's on her way, but she can't get
through. They've closed off the roads.

527
00:38:36,523 --> 00:38:37,774
There's thousands of people
trying to get in.

528
00:38:37,857 --> 00:38:39,234
The whole city's come to a halt.

529
00:38:39,317 --> 00:38:42,487
And Dad phoned, it's on the news
and everything. He was crying.

530
00:38:42,570 --> 00:38:44,739
Oh, my God, I've been a mess.

531
00:38:44,864 --> 00:38:49,118
But what happened? I mean,
what really happened? Where were you?

532
00:38:49,202 --> 00:38:50,912
MAN ON RADIO: Eyewitness reports

533
00:38:50,995 --> 00:38:52,872
from the Royal Hope Hospital
continue to pour in,

534
00:38:52,956 --> 00:38:55,250
and all seem to be
remarkably consistent.

535
00:38:55,333 --> 00:38:58,211
This from medical student
Oliver Morgenstern.

536
00:38:59,087 --> 00:39:00,380
I was there.

537
00:39:00,463 --> 00:39:05,134
I saw it happen
and I feel uniquely privileged.

538
00:39:05,260 --> 00:39:07,846
I looked out at the surface of the moon.

539
00:39:07,929 --> 00:39:14,018
I saw the Earth suspended in space,
and it all just proves Mr Saxon right.

540
00:39:14,102 --> 00:39:16,187
We're not alone in the universe.

541
00:39:16,312 --> 00:39:20,775
There's life out there.
Wild and extraordinary life.

542
00:39:20,859 --> 00:39:23,528
I am not staying in there
to be insulted!

543
00:39:23,653 --> 00:39:26,447
She didn't mean it, sweetheart.
She was just saying you look healthy.

544
00:39:26,531 --> 00:39:28,366
No, I did not. I said orange.

545
00:39:28,449 --> 00:39:31,202
Clive, that woman is disrespecting me.
She's never liked me.

546
00:39:31,286 --> 00:39:34,122
Oh, I can't think why,
after you stole my husband!

547
00:39:34,247 --> 00:39:37,000
I was seduced!
I'm entirely innocent. Tell her, babes!

548
00:39:37,125 --> 00:39:38,585
And then she has a go at Martha,

549
00:39:38,668 --> 00:39:40,461
practically accused her
of making the whole thing up.

550
00:39:40,545 --> 00:39:42,672
Mum, I don't mind. Just leave it.

551
00:39:42,797 --> 00:39:45,133
Oh, "I've been to the moon." As if!

552
00:39:45,216 --> 00:39:47,302
They were drugged.
It said so on the news.

553
00:39:47,385 --> 00:39:51,097
Since when did you watch the news?
You can't handle Quizmania.

554
00:39:51,180 --> 00:39:53,433
Annalise started it.
She did, I heard her.

555
00:39:53,516 --> 00:39:55,852
-Tish, don't make it worse.
-Come off it, Leo.

556
00:39:55,977 --> 00:39:58,313
What did she buy you? Soap!
A 75 pence soap!

557
00:39:58,396 --> 00:40:00,148
I'm never talking to your family again!

558
00:40:00,231 --> 00:40:02,817
-Stay! Have a nice party!
-Don't you dare!

559
00:40:02,942 --> 00:40:05,653
-I'm putting my foot down!
-Make a fool of yourself!

560
00:40:05,737 --> 00:40:07,655
This is me, putting my foot down!

561
00:40:07,780 --> 00:40:11,159
God knows you've been doing it
for the last 25 years. Why stop now?

562
00:40:11,284 --> 00:40:14,245
Mum, don't. I asked the DJ
and he's playing that song later...

563
00:40:51,366 --> 00:40:53,660
I went to the moon today.

564
00:40:53,743 --> 00:40:56,329
Bit more peaceful than down here.

565
00:40:56,412 --> 00:40:59,123
You never even told me who you are.

566
00:40:59,207 --> 00:41:00,625
The Doctor.

567
00:41:00,708 --> 00:41:04,545
But what sort of species?
It's not every day I get to ask that.

568
00:41:04,671 --> 00:41:06,172
I'm a Time Lord.

569
00:41:06,297 --> 00:41:09,425
Right. Not pompous at all, then.

570
00:41:10,551 --> 00:41:12,220
I just thought,

571
00:41:12,345 --> 00:41:15,682
since you saved my life and
I've got a brand-new sonic screwdriver

572
00:41:15,765 --> 00:41:17,934
which needs road-testing,

573
00:41:18,059 --> 00:41:20,103
you might fancy a trip.

574
00:41:20,186 --> 00:41:22,897
What, into space?

575
00:41:23,022 --> 00:41:25,566
I can't, I've got exams.
I've got things to do.

576
00:41:25,650 --> 00:41:28,945
I have to go into town first thing and
pay the rent. I got my family going mad.

577
00:41:29,028 --> 00:41:33,324
If it helps,
I can travel in time as well.

578
00:41:33,408 --> 00:41:35,076
-Get out of here.
-I can!

579
00:41:35,201 --> 00:41:38,788
-Come on now, that is going too far.
-I'll prove it.

580
00:41:41,541 --> 00:41:43,751
(WHOOSHING)

581
00:42:05,648 --> 00:42:06,941
Told you!

582
00:42:07,025 --> 00:42:10,486
No, but... That was this morning.

583
00:42:10,570 --> 00:42:12,780
But... Did you...

584
00:42:12,864 --> 00:42:15,533
Oh, my God, you can travel in time!

585
00:42:15,616 --> 00:42:17,535
But hold on,
if you could see me this morning,

586
00:42:17,618 --> 00:42:20,121
why didn't you tell me
not to go into work?

587
00:42:20,204 --> 00:42:23,708
Crossing into established events
is strictly forbidden.

588
00:42:23,791 --> 00:42:26,210
Except for cheap tricks.

589
00:42:26,294 --> 00:42:28,129
And that's your spaceship?

590
00:42:28,212 --> 00:42:30,214
It's called the Tardis.

591
00:42:30,298 --> 00:42:33,092
Time And Relative Dimension In Space.

592
00:42:33,176 --> 00:42:35,887
Your spaceship's made of wood.

593
00:42:35,970 --> 00:42:39,098
There's not much room,
we'd be a bit intimate.

594
00:42:40,641 --> 00:42:42,185
Take a look.

595
00:42:50,777 --> 00:42:52,820
No, no, no...

596
00:42:53,946 --> 00:42:55,823
But it's just a box.

597
00:42:56,866 --> 00:42:58,701
But it's huge!

598
00:42:58,785 --> 00:43:00,495
How does it do that?

599
00:43:00,620 --> 00:43:02,663
It's wood!

600
00:43:02,789 --> 00:43:05,750
It's like a box
with that room just crammed in.

601
00:43:07,960 --> 00:43:09,629
It's bigger on the inside!

602
00:43:09,712 --> 00:43:11,798
Is it? I hadn't noticed.

603
00:43:13,424 --> 00:43:15,843
All right then, let's get going.

604
00:43:15,968 --> 00:43:18,513
But is there a crew?

605
00:43:18,638 --> 00:43:21,265
Like a navigator and stuff?
Where is everyone?

606
00:43:21,349 --> 00:43:23,476
Just me.

607
00:43:23,559 --> 00:43:24,852
All on your own?

608
00:43:24,977 --> 00:43:27,563
Well, sometimes I have guests.

609
00:43:27,688 --> 00:43:29,690
I mean, some friends
travelling alongside me.

610
00:43:29,816 --> 00:43:31,609
I had... It was recently...

611
00:43:31,692 --> 00:43:33,611
Friend of mine.

612
00:43:33,736 --> 00:43:36,823
Rose, her name was. Rose and...

613
00:43:38,199 --> 00:43:40,535
We were together. Anyway...

614
00:43:40,660 --> 00:43:41,744
Where is she now?

615
00:43:41,869 --> 00:43:44,580
With her family.
Happy. She's fine, she's...

616
00:43:44,705 --> 00:43:47,291
-Not that you're replacing her!
-Never said I was.

617
00:43:47,375 --> 00:43:51,504
Just one trip. To say thanks.
You get one trip then back home.

618
00:43:52,088 --> 00:43:54,173
I'd rather be on my own.

619
00:43:56,634 --> 00:43:59,053
Well, you're the one that kissed me.

620
00:43:59,178 --> 00:44:01,430
That was a genetic transfer.

621
00:44:03,391 --> 00:44:06,853
-And if you will wear a tight suit...
-Now, don't.

622
00:44:06,936 --> 00:44:10,898
And then travel all the way across
the universe just to ask me on a date.

623
00:44:10,982 --> 00:44:12,275
Stop it!

624
00:44:13,234 --> 00:44:16,028
For the record,
I'm not remotely interested.

625
00:44:16,737 --> 00:44:18,906
I only go for humans.

626
00:44:20,324 --> 00:44:21,492
Good!

627
00:44:21,576 --> 00:44:24,954
Now then, close down
the Gravitic Anomalyser.

628
00:44:25,079 --> 00:44:27,081
Fire up the Helmic Regulator.

629
00:44:27,165 --> 00:44:30,418
And finally, the handbrake.

630
00:44:32,712 --> 00:44:33,880
Ready?

631
00:44:34,005 --> 00:44:35,506
No.

632
00:44:35,631 --> 00:44:37,300
Off we go!

633
00:44:39,802 --> 00:44:42,388
Blimey! It's a bit bumpy!

634
00:44:42,471 --> 00:44:44,724
Welcome aboard, Miss Jones.

635
00:44:45,600 --> 00:44:47,727
It's my pleasure, Mr Smith.

636
00:44:58,321 --> 00:45:01,866
The Globe Theatre,
containing the man himself.

637
00:45:01,949 --> 00:45:04,202
Shut your big, fat mouths!

638
00:45:04,285 --> 00:45:06,704
-Mr Shakespeare, isn't it?
-No autographs.

639
00:45:06,787 --> 00:45:09,207
Love's Labour's Won
will never be played.

640
00:45:09,290 --> 00:45:11,542
Upon this night the work is done.

641
00:45:11,626 --> 00:45:12,752
Witchcraft.

642
00:45:12,835 --> 00:45:14,045
(CACKLING)

643
00:45:14,128 --> 00:45:15,546
Impossible!

644
00:45:15,630 --> 00:45:17,506
Hey, nonny, nonny!

645
00:45:17,632 --> 00:45:18,966
No!

646
00:45:19,091 --> 00:45:20,801
DOCTOR: The entire future
of the human race,

647
00:45:20,927 --> 00:45:24,513
it ends right now, in 1599,
if we don't stop it.

648
00:45:24,597 --> 00:45:25,723
By-da-boom-ba!

649
00:45:25,806 --> 00:45:27,558
That's quite good.

